<section class="section" data-sec="narrative">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="sec-head"><div><span class="no">The chapter</span><h2>The lay of the land</h2></div></div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Old Northeast is the neighborhood people picture when they picture St. Pete: a 1910s&ndash;1920s
      grid of craftsman bungalows, Mediterranean revivals, and four-square colonials running from
      downtown&rsquo;s edge to Coffee Pot Bayou. The brick streets and granite curbs aren&rsquo;t a marketing
      line &mdash; they&rsquo;re city-protected, and they&rsquo;re a big part of why homes here hold value the way
      they do.</p>
      <p>What the listings don&rsquo;t tell you: inventory is structurally tight. Most owners stay for
      decades, tear-downs are rare and contested, and the best blocks trade quietly &mdash; often before
      a sign goes up. If you&rsquo;re buying here, being ready matters more than being patient.</p>
      {#- Heading below is the bound recast of the fair-housing finding:
          describe what living HERE is like (place), never who should live here. -#}
      <h3>What it&rsquo;s like to live here</h3>
      <p>Front porches face the street, the waterfront trail is ten minutes on foot, and
      downtown&rsquo;s restaurants are fifteen. The trade: older homes mean older systems &mdash;
      insurance, electrical, and sewer laterals belong on the inspection checklist, and the
      flood box below covers what zone a block sits in before anyone falls in love.</p>
      <p class="draftnote">DRAFT narrative, shown as sample &mdash; the shipped chapter is produced by the
      KB pipeline from sourced facts and reviewed by the broker before it publishes (nothing
      auto-publishes).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

